50|$|In January 2007 Horgan accused Premier Gordon Campbell of conflict-of-interest, due to owning {{shares of}} Alcan while signing an order-in-council {{approving}} {{an agreement between}} Alcan and BC Hydro which was subsequently overturned by the Utilities Commission as being not in the public interest. The Ethic Commissioner cleared Campbell of wrongdoing but made a recommendation that cabinet ministers and other senior officials place their assets in <b>blind</b> <b>trusts.</b> Horgan subsequently introduced this recommendation as the private member bill Members' Conflict of Interest Amendment Act {{in the third and}} fourth sessions and, similar but more comprehensive bill, in line with the Federal Accountability Act, but they were not advanced beyond first reading.|$|R
